ce:section.ce:para:
The morphology and surface structural features of the synthesized N-CDs were characterized using TEM, XRD, FT-IR, and XPS. Fig. 2a shows the TEM and HRTEM images of the as-prepared N-CDs. The synthesized N-CDs exhibited spherical particles with size ranging 1.5–5.0 nm, showing good dispersion. The size distribution of the N-CDs is shown in the inset of Fig. 2a, with an average size of 3.83 ± 0.82 nm. In the HRTEM image of the N-CDs (inset of Fig. 2a), a crystal lattice of 0.21 nm was observed, which was similar to the (102) planes of graphite (sp

                           2
                        ) carbon (Z. Lin et al., 2024b; Shi et al., 2016). The XRD patterns of the N-CDs (Fig. S1) illustrate a broad diffraction peak at 20.20° (2θ) with characteristic of amorphous carbon. The TEM and XRD results showed the formation of amorphous carbon from the precursor during the microwave process. The FT-IR spectra of the N-CDs in Fig. 2b showed a broad and dispersed absorption band in the range 3600–2500 cm−1, which is attributed to the stretching vibration of OH in carboxylic acid. The strong absorption at 1718 cm−1 was assigned to the stretching vibration peak of CO in carboxylic acid, whereas peaks at 1680 and 1600 cm−1 were attributed to the stretching vibrations of CN and CC, respectively. The peaks at 1244 and 1405 cm−1 correspond to the stretching vibrations of CO and CN, respectively, whereas the peak at 1115 cm−1 corresponds to the stretching vibration of C-O(H) (Hu et al., 2022; Khan, Wang, & Wang, 2018). The FT-IR spectra revealed the presence of functional groups, such as carboxyl, amide, ester bonds, and hydroxyl groups, on the surface of the N-CDs.
